        {
          "type": "figure",
          "id": "fig-ch03_03_08",
          "caption": {
            "segmentId": "m66441:caption:fig-ch03_03_08-caption"
          },
          "media": {
            "id": "fs-id1442842",
            "alt": "The molecular structure of a phospholipid is shown. It consists of two fatty acids attached to the first and second carbons in glycerol, and a phosphate group attached to the third position. In the illustration one of the fatty acids is saturated and straight, and the second is unsaturated and bent. Both are below the glycerol molecule. The phosphate group may be further modified by addition of another molecule to one of its oxygens indicated by upper-case R. Two molecules may modify the phosphate group, choline and serine. The glycerol and phosphate group make up the hydrophilic head of the molecule, while the fatty acids attached below make up the hydrophobic tails.",
            "src": "../../media/Figure_03_03_08.png",
            "mimeType": "image/png"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "para",
          "id": "fs-id1953709",
          "segmentId": "m66441:para:fs-id1953709"
        },
        {
          "type": "figure",
          "id": "fig-ch03_03_09",
          "caption": {
            "segmentId": "m66441:caption:fig-ch03_03_09-caption"
          },
          "media": {
            "id": "fs-id1437221",
            "alt": "An illustration of a phospholipids bilayer is shown. The phospholipids bilayer consists of two layers of phospholipids. The hydrophobic tails of the phospholipids face one another while the hydrophilic head groups face outward.",
            "src": "../../media/Figure_03_03_09-0814.jpg",
            "mimeType": "image/jpg"
          }
        },
